input: How can a drought impact food supplies, and what effect does this change have?
output: A drought can have a number of impacts on food supplies.  First, it can affect the availability of water for agricultural purposes, which will impact the amount of land that can be used to grow crops.  If the amount of land available for growing crops is limited, this will impact how much food is available for human consumption.  Second, drought can impact the ability of farmers to grow crops, as they may no longer have enough water to irrigate their fields.  This can increase the cost of food, as farmers may need to purchase more water to maintain the crops they are growing.  Third, drought can impact the ability of farmers to reap the crops that they have grown, as they may not have the water necessary to be able to harvest the crops.  If the crops cannot be reaped, then they cannot be sold, which can increase the cost of food.  Fourth, drought can impact the ability of farmers to grow crops, as they may not have the labor available to plant, grow and harvest those crops.  If farmers do not have the labor available to grow crops, this can increase the cost of food.  Fifth, drought can impact the ability of farmers to produce crops, as they may not have the equipment available to plant, grow and harvest those crops.  If farmers do not have the equipment available to plant, grow and harvest those crops, this can increase the cost of food.  Finally, drought can impact the ability of food to be transported to market, as trucks and other means of transportation may not be able to navigate around areas with limited water supplies.  If food cannot be transported to market, this can increase the cost of food.  A combination of these impacts can lead to increased food costs.
label: A drought can reduce the amount of crops that can be grown due to less water being available for the farms in an area. input: Who is Romain Iannetta
output:
Romain Iannetta (born November 24, 1988) is a Canadian former professional ice hockey left winger who played in one game in the National Hockey League (NHL) for the Colorado Avalanche during the 2012–13 season. He currently plays for the Frisco Wind, a ECHL affiliate of the Dallas Stars, as well as the Quebec Rocket of the American Hockey League (AHL).

Playing career
After playing four seasons with the Quebec Remparts of the QMJHL, Iannetta was drafted by the Colorado Avalanche in the sixth round, 179th overall at the 2008 NHL Entry Draft. He played 40 games for the Avalanche's American Hockey League (AHL) affiliate, the Colorado Eagles, in the 2011–12 season, where he scored 10 goals and 25 points. On August 17, 2012, the Avalanche recalled Iannetta from the Eagles for his first NHL game, where he recorded an assist in a 5–2 win over the Florida Panthers. Prior to his NHL stint, Iannetta played for the Colorado Eagles during the 2012 Calder Cup playoffs.

On February 25, 2013, Iannetta was assigned to play with the Avalanche's top developmental affiliate, the Colorado Springs Sky Sox, to end the regular season. He scored a goal in his first game with the Sky Sox.

On July 5, 2014, Iannetta was traded, along with a third-round pick in the 2016 NHL Entry Draft, to the Edmonton Oilers in exchange for Steve MacIntyre.

On July 1, 2015, Iannetta signed a one year contract with Swiss club, SC Bern of the National League A (NLA).
On July 5, 2016, Iannetta left the NLA, signing a one-year contract with Austrian club, EC KAC of the 2. Liga.

On July 1, 2017, Iannetta returned to EC KAC, now known as EC Visé, for the 2017–18 season.

input: What is the origin of man?
output: The origin of modern humans is a subject of debate among scientists, with evidence that points to several different origins. The oldest and most widely accepted is the finding of a 1.18 million year old skull in Germany that has been classified as a direct ancestor to all humans. Other families of humans that have been shown to be direct ancestors include the Neanderthals and the Denisovans. ADNA evidence from a Homo heidelbergensis child from Dusseldorf, Germany, has also been used to support this theory. The theory that all non-African humans share a common last common ancestor is also supported by genetic, fossil, and morphological data. The most widely accepted theory is that humans arose in Africa and subsequently migrated to other parts of the world.
label:
Homo sapiens
Anatomically modern humans emerged around 300,000 years ago in Africa, evolving from Homo heidelbergensis or a similar species and migrating out of Africa, gradually replacing or interbreeding with local populations of archaic humans. For most of history, humans were nomadic hunter-gatherers.

In organic chemistry, isothiocyanate is the functional group −N=C=S, formed by substituting the oxygen in the isocyanate group with a sulfur. These natural isothiocyanates, such as allyl isothiocyanate, are also known as mustard oils. An artificial isothiocyanate, phenyl isothiocyanate, is used for amino acid sequencing in the Edman degradation.

Cruciferous vegetables, such as bok choy, broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower, kale, and others, are rich sources of glucosinolate precursors of isothiocyanates. input: Why some people are more stressed than others and how to manage stress?
output:
Stress can come from within us. Things like personal problems, financial worries, relationship issues, work pressures, etc. These can build up over time and can have a damaging impact on our mental and physical health.

Other sources of stress may be more external, such as a busy schedule, pressure from others, etc.

The way we react to stress is also important. We all have the capacity to respond constructively in the face of adversity. Effective stress management helps us to use this ability constructively. At a physiological level, we need to rest and relax so that our body can fully recover from the demands of the stressor. We also need to think clearly and make good decisions.

At a mental level, we need to find a sense of perspective, be able to manage our anxiety and focus on the positive side of things. Effective stress management can help us to establish a sense of resilience and the ability to bounce back quickly from setbacks.

Many of us do not have the ability to effectively manage our stress. We tend to use food, alcohol or drugs as a way to suppress negative feelings. This can often lead to poor health and a lack of well-being.

It is important to understand the sources of stress in our lives and to develop a plan for effective management. This will help to ensure that we are able to live healthier and happier lives.

Some are born with this quality to manage hard and tricky situations with a cool behaviour, but for others it is tricky and they really need to train themselves to certain situations.When a person is stressed, it is always best they share their feelings with someone they trust.In a stressful situation, the natural response of our body is the release of Cortisol, which is the primary hormone which gets released and a good physical exercise routine can help in managing it.Prolonged stress leads to complicated issues such as Anxiety and  Depression which could be managed by practicing some relaxation techniques such as Yoga and Deep breathing.

It is also one of the largest employers of native Hawaiians, with many residents choosing to work in the industry after moving to the state. input: What is Targetted Allele-Specific CRISPR/Cas9 Activation (TASCA)?
output:
TASCA is a recently developed genome-editing technology which allows the precise modification of DNA at selected genomic loci using only a sgRNA (single guide RNA) and Cas9 nuclease. The use of only a single guide RNA significantly reduces off-target effects compared to other genome-editing technologies such as Zinc Finger Nucleases (ZFNs) and Transcription Activator-Like Effector Nucleases (TALENs).

The CRISPR/Cas9 system is a prokaryotic immune system which uses a short guiding RNA to detect and destroy foreign DNA elements. The RNA directs the Cas9 endonuclease to a specific site in the genome and the nuclease recognizes the "protospacer" sequence on the foreign DNA and cuts the DNA at that site.

In TASCA, a short "activation" guide RNA is used which contains a sequence complementary to a sequence in the targeted DNA locus. When the two guide RNAs are expressed in the cell (usually as a chimeric transcript), the guide RNA that matches the activation sequence will give it priority to bind to the target DNA and the "activation" guide RNA will be able to bind to the "normal" guide RNA that would activate the Cas9 nuclease.

This gives the possibility to activate only the target locus and not affect other genomic loci which contain the "normal" guide RNA and the Cas9 nuclease.

The activation guide RNA can be designed to promote the expression of a gene of interest (that is normally silenced) or to inactivate a gene of interest, or to activate a cell's own DNA at a specific locus.

There are no ethical concerns in terms of using the TASCA technology, as the activation guide RNA is designed using publicly available algorithms and does not contain a Cas9 nuclease recognition sequence, so it does not induce Cas9 nuclease activity.

In September 2018, TASCA was featured on the cover of the journal eLIFE.
label:
The CRISPR/Cas9 system is a gene editing technology that allows for precise modification of the DNA sequence of a genome. Targetted Allele-Specific CRISPR/Cas9 Activation (TASCA) enables researchers to selectively activate a specific gene within a genome by targeting specific sequences of DNA and inducing the expression of the desired gene.

TASCA can be used in a variety of applications, such as gene therapy, drug discovery, and basic research on gene function. It offers a powerful tool for studying the role of specific genes in cellular processes and disease states.

input: What characterizes turbulent flow
output: Turbulent flow is characterized by dramatic changes in a fluid's properties. Turbulence occurs when there are chaotic changes in flow due to interactions between fluid particles. These chaotic changes cause pressure and velocity fluctuations in the fluid that are relatively large compared with the mean values for these variables. Turbulence can be found in a wide range of natural phenomena, such as the flow of air through a jet engine, the movement of water through a riverbed, or the flow of blood through the circulatory system. Turbulence is also found in many engineering systems, including heat exchangers, turbochargers, and liquid rocket engines. Turbulence can negatively affect the performance of many systems, such as those in aircraft and heat exchangers. In liquid rocket engines, turbulence can hinder performance because it reduces the amount of thrust that the engine can produce.
label: Turbulent flow is characterized by chaotic changes in pressure and flow velocity.

While still a student at the University of Helsinki, Torvalds started developing Linux to create a system similar to MINIX, a UNIX operating system. In 1991 he released version 0.02; Version 1.0 of the Linux kernel, the core of the operating system, was released in 1994. About the same time, American software developer Richard Stallman and the FSF made efforts to create an open-source UNIX-like operating system called GNU. input: What is the greenhouse effect?
output:
The greenhouse effect is the natural process by which the Earth's atmosphere helps to regulate the temperature of the planet. Warm air in the atmosphere naturally rises, while cold air tends to fall. This natural process is called convection, and it is what causes the movements of air that we experience every day.

The greenhouse effect is a natural process that plays a critical role in regulating the temperature of the planet. In actuality, the greenhouse effect helps regulate the temperature of the planet far above what is needed for human or animal survival.

The greenhouse gases in the atmosphere such as water vapor, carbon dioxide, and methane absorb and emit thermal radiation, or light. This process helps to keep the planet at a relatively steady temperature, while allowing the planet to naturally regulate itself.

While the greenhouse gases are needed for the natural regulation of the planet, too much of a good thing can be a bad thing. The buildup of these gases in the atmosphere has led to the well-known effect of global warming.

input: What is the difference between AWD and 4WD?
output: In addition to utilizing 4WD when appropriate, AWD allows the vehicle to distribute torque to all of its drive wheels instead of only the wheels in high- traction situations. When AWD is not needed, 4WD can help distribute torque to the road the vehicle best supports drive.
label:
AWD is a system that without driver intervention, shifts power between the rear and front wheels. This system is typically found on light-duty SUVs or passenger cars. The AWD drive system is designed for mild inclement weather conditions such as light snow, ice and rain. It is not designed for off-roading or severe weather conditions such as heavy snow or mud. This is where the 4WD system comes into the picture. 

4WD is a system that includes a transfer case that directly applies power to the rear axle, both front and rear axles and in some cases, only to the front axle. In addition, some 4WD systems include lower gear ratio options, locking hubs and lockers in the axles that force an equal amount of power to each wheel. All this taken together enables a 4WD system to enable a vehicle to navigate through deep snow, mud, over rocks and other obstacles with ease. The 4WD system is most commonly found on trucks, Jeeps and other purpose-built vehicles designed for heavy-duty use, whether for work or pleasure.

input: Extract the key bulletpoints I need to know about University of Oxford

The Oxford colleges are dedicated to individual saints: Balliol to St. John the Baptist, Merton to St. Thomas à Becket, Christ Church to St. Mary the Virgin, and Oriel to St. Michael and All Angels.

- Founded as a centre for training priests in England in the 12th century, the University of Oxford is one of the oldest institutions of higher education in the world. It has existed in some form since the 11th century. The first 36 colleges were registered in 1555; the current number of colleges and halls is 132. The university is formally incorporated as a body corporate with a royal charter, and is therefore a royal title.

- Oxford is home to the world's oldest university graduate in history, who became a member of the prestigious College Common Room in 1522, and the first person to receive a degree from the University of Oxford, John Colet. The university has educated many notable people throughout history, including Charles Darwin, Charles Dickens, Benjamin Disraeli, Florence Nightingale, Stephen Hawking, and more.

input: What is the gun culture in the United States?

However, more than 200 years later, the 2nd Amendment no longer solely ties itself to its original intent: to protect itself and its people. The prevalence of guns in the United States has led to the United States having the highest gun ownership rates in the world. While no one can say for sure how many shows they will end up writing for, the number of shows that "Jesus Christ Superstar," for which he wrote the music and lyrics as well as the book, the Tony Award winning "The Apple Tree," and "Hair" for which he also wrote the book, are, are all safe bets for him staying active for a very long time. The songwriting team of Rogers & Hammerstein was the first to use songs to further the plot vs. break the plot for a song and dance. Their musicals are still enormously popular and performed constantly. They include "Oklahoma", "The King & I", and "The Sound of Music". Leonard Bernstein, while most known for classical music made a major contribution to musicals with the groundbreaking "West Side Story", an updated Romeo and Juliet story with spectacular music, every song a classic. While he is often criticized for not having "hummable" melodies, his genius is undeniable, and he did have one bonafide hit with "Send in

input: What batting traits make a good baseball or softball hitter?
output: A good hitter is a cool-headed hitter. They should be able to stay balanced in the batters box and have good focus on the pitcher they are hitting against. A good hitter is also able to read the pitchers ball flight. Good batters are able to recognize balls that are out of the fielders reach and are able to adjust their hitting pattern to compensate for the ball.
label:
There are many traits that great baseball and softball batters share.  Some of the most important are extreme confidence, sound batting mechanics, and coordination developed though a combination of talent and practice.  

All great hitters share some consistencies in their batting mechanics such as their lower half mechanics, their hand and bat path, and their head and eye movement.

With their lower half mechanics they generate powerful torque from the ground up by timing the planting their feet in a balanced position and forcefully rotating and opening their hips.  Hitting powerful line drives relies heavily on the barrel of the bat meeting the ball flush.  Batters increase the odds of this by keeping their hands in, connected to the back shoulder, and having one palm facing up and one palm facing down for as long as possible as the bat path travels through the strike zone.  Finally, all great hitters maintain consistent head and eye position throughout the motion. 

There are many nuances of batting mechanics that all great hitters share but these are some of the most important.

output: Because Fiona is the only one allergic to sunflowers, she was not in the auditorium during the graduation ceremony when the graduation committee handed out the diplomas. input: When was George Washington born?

input: How can Bernoulli's principle be derived from Newton's second law of motion?
output: Newton's second law of motion, F=ma, can be expressed in differential form as MV=ma, where M is the net force acting on an object, V is the velocity of the object, and a is the acceleration of the object. Since F=MV, then MV=ma, which can be simplified to V2+2aV=ma, which can be further simplified to aV2=ma. Substituting in a from the left side of the equation and rearranging yields MV=ma, which is equivalent to Newton's second law of motion.
label: Bernoulli's principle can be derived directly from Isaac Newton's second Law of Motion. If a small volume of fluid is flowing horizontally from a region of high pressure to a region of low pressure, then there is more pressure behind than in front. This gives a net force on the volume, accelerating it along the streamline.

input: What kind of language is Shauraseni Prakrit
output: Shauraseni is a language which was in use in ancient India. It is a descendant of the classical Prakrits of Northern India. Some classify it as a branch of the Prakrits called Apabhraṃśa, which is a northern Prakrit family. Shauraseni is closely related to the modern spoken Kharoṣṭhi, and is very similar to it, but differs in some phonological and morphological respects.
label:
Shauraseni Prakrit was a Middle Indo-Aryan language and a Dramatic Prakrit. Shauraseni was the chief language used in drama in medieval northern India. Most of the material in this language originates from the 3rd to 10th centuries, though it was probably a spoken vernacular around the 2nd century BCE in the ancient state of Surasena. 

Among the Prakrits, Shauraseni is said to be the one most closely related to Classical Sanskrit in that it is derived from the Old Indian Indo-Aryan dialect of the Madhyadesa on which Classical Sanskrit was mainly based. Its descendants include the languages of the Hindi Belt, the Central Zone of modern Indo-Aryan or Hindi languages, the standard registers of the Hindustani language based on the Delhi dialect.

input: Why Rafael Nadal succeeds on clay?
output: Rafael Nadal is considered as the best clay court player in the world. He has won 14 singles titles on clay courts and has won the Rome Masters seven times. He has a record of 76-4 on clay which is the best winning record in the history of clay court tennis.

Several have compared the Spaniard displaying his prowess on the red dirt to Picasso painting a live mural, Ennio Morricone producing a melody exactly congruent with the scenario, or Jorge Lorenzo posting similar times lap after lap in an almost mechanical yet fluid approach.

Rafael Nadal's ability on clay is mostly due to the surface itself. This may appear to be a quip, but the particular qualities of claycourts - which distinguish them from grass and hardcourts - are a fundamental reason why Rafael Nadal has dominated the surface the way he has.

What distinguishes clay? It's sluggish and bouncy. Fundamentally, clay reduces the speed of the ball once it bounces on the surface. Of course, there's more to it than just making the game slow and monotonous, but that's the distinguishing quality of a claycourt.

The surface is also less skiddish than grass or hard, allowing the ball to bounce high, which suits Rafael Nadal's high topspin-based game.

These are the Seven Wonders of the World:
1. Great Pyramid of Giza, near Cairo, Egypt - This is widely considered the oldest of the Seven Wonders and the only one to remain intact until today. It was built as a tomb for the ancient Egyptian pharoah Khufu around 2580 BC.
2. Colossus of Rhodes, in the Island of Rhodes - This was a statue of the Greek god Helios that was originally built to commemorate the victory of Rhodes over the Persians at the Battle of Salamis in 480 BC.
3. Temple of Artemis, near Ephesus, Turkey - This was a Greco-Buddhist temple dedicated to the goddess Artemis and built in the 5th century BC.
4. Mausoleum at Halicarnassus, near ancient Halicarnassus, on the coast of the Eastern Mediterranean - This was a monument built by the Mausolus of Caria for himself, his wife and his son after they had been killed in battle by the Scythian king Hydrus.
5. Lighthouse of Alexandria, Egypt - This was a tower on the western edge of the city of Alexandria in Egypt. It was built in the 4th century BC.
6. Statue of Zeus at Olympia, Greece - This was a statue of the Greco-Buddhist Zeus that was dedicated by the Ancient Olympic Committee in the early 5th century BC.
7. Great Wall of China, on the border between northeaster China and Manchuria - This was a massive fortification project started during the Qin dynasty in the 3rd century BC.

input: what is the difference between ARM and x86 chipsets?
output: ARM and x86 are semiconductor instruction sets.  It is how your motherboard talks to your computer's processor.  The x86 instruction set is over 20 years old and was designed to support the Pentium processor.  As a result, the x86 instruction set is very simple and is best described as a set of assembly languages.  The x86 instruction set is a stack based architecture where the processor can only execute one task at a time.  The x86 instruction set is a very limited architecture and is best described as a set of assembly languages.  The most popular x86 processor is the Intel i5 and i7 series of processors.  The big difference between x86 and the newer ARM architecture is that the ARM architecture is designed to support a much newer class of processors.  These new processors are called mobile or smartphone processors.  The most popular mobile processor is the Apple A series processor.
label: ARM uses Reduced Instruction Set Computing Architecture (RISC) whereas x86 uses Complex Instruction Set Computing Architecture (CISC). ARM executes single instruction per cycle whereas x86 executes complex instructions in multiple cycles. This allows softwares to be optimized for performance against ARM chipset as opposed to an 86 hardware approach to optimize. It would also be interesting to mention that ARM uses higher memory and less registers compared to x86.

input: How are odds different from probability?
output: The difference between probability and odds is that probability assumes every event is equally likely, while odds takes into account all relevant factors that affect the likelihood of an event happening. For example, if you're playing craps, the probability of getting a seven on a roll of two is 20 percent, but the odds of that happening are 1 in 6 (or 16.67 percent).
label: Both are measurements for how likely it is for an event to occur. Odds are commonly used in gambling, which probability is a measure that is commonly used in mathematics/statistics. In statistics, probability measures the number of outcomes in which a particular event occurred divided by the total number of possible outcomes. For example, the probability of rain on a given day would be based on, historically with similar conditions, the number of rainy days divided by a total number of days. The odds are measured as the number of events divided by the number of non-events. To contrast, probability would be the number of events divided by the sum of events and non-events.

input: What is the history of Tax Day in the United States?
output: The phrase "tax day" is most often associated with April 15th, the day when taxes must be filed for individual or business entities in the United States.  The day was first created by union activists and was the result of Congress increasing taxes on corporate America in 1894.  That tax increase was very unpopular with corporations and the business community and they used the slogan "make tax day" to pressure congress into reducing the taxes.  In 1934 President Roosevelt pushed for a national holiday for filing taxes, and in 1974 the Tax Foundation named April 15th as National Tax Day.
label:
Tax Day exists as a deadline for many United States residents to report earnings in order to pay income taxes.

The United States introduced the income tax in 1861 in order to fund the American Civil War. This was later deemed unconstitutional and repealed in 1872. This was later reenacted in 1894 as part of the Revenue Act with its constitutionality settled in the Sixteenth Amendment to the Constitution in 1913. Tax day was initially set for March in 1913 and was eventually moved to April 15th in 1955.

label: Humpback whales will typically feed in the summer months off the rich waters of Alaska, northern Canada and eastern Russia, and begin their migration to warmer waters of Hawaii or Mexico starting in mid-fall to breed. They will stay in warmer regions to breed and calve their babies during winter, and will start their migration back to the polar regions by late March or April. input: How to do forecasting with small dataset?
output: You can use many machine learning techniques like linear regression, random forest, gradient boosting machines, etc to do forecasting with small dataset. You can also use simple methods like using historical data to make a educated guess.
label:
Forecasting with small datasets can be challenging, as many traditional methods require larger amounts of data for accurate predictions.
Here are few approaches that can help you.

Simple moving average: This involves taking the average of a certain number of past data points, and using it as the forecast for the next period. This method can be effective for stable time series with no trend or seasonality.

Exponential smoothing: This method assigns exponentially decreasing weights to past observations, with more recent observations being given more weight. This method can be effective for time series with trend and/or seasonality.

ARIMA: The AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) model is a popular choice for time series forecasting. It can be effective for small datasets if the underlying data follows a pattern that can be modeled using an ARIMA model.

input: Netflix views streaming video as a "sustaining" technology that extends its core mail DVD business. Do you agree with this, or do you think streaming video is a "disruptive" technology for Netflix that does not align with its core business and requires a different strategy?
output:
I think streaming video is a sustaining technology for Netflix because it allows the company to extend its core business of producing and distributing DVDs. Netflix does not need to worry about the hardware and software to stream video, because it is already doing this. It also means that the content that Netflix produces does not need to be limited to DVDs that can be stored in a DVD player. Netflix can also produce video content for streaming that can be viewed on any device with an Internet connection. Therefore, the streaming video technology is highly complementary to the DVDs business.

However, I do agree that the streaming video business is different from the DVDs business. For DVDs, Netflix could predict that people would continue to want to own physical DVDs and that the market for streaming video would be limited. However, with streaming video, there is no "middleman" to charge extra for: Netflix is the middleman, and it is providing the streaming video service. Therefore, Netflix needs to worry about keeping streaming video services free or close to free, because there is no "cost" to the middleman. The middleman fees are for DVDs, where there is a middleman. Therefore, Netflix should rethink its strategy for streaming video and think more like a traditional company, in which the streaming video service is a loss-leader to attract customers to the DVDs business.
label: Netflix did a strategic renewal by cannibalizing its own cash cow business of mail-in-DVD services. This was the right move as internet speeds were increasing and moving towards broadband. Netflix was even considering launching a TV box if internet speeds remained constant. I agree that streaming video is a disruptive technology for Netflix, requiring a different strategy. Adopting a disruptive technology, Netflix forced Blockbuster to offer the mail-in-DVD service. By the time Blockbuster offered the mail-in-DVD service, Netflix had already begun experimenting with streaming videos and had started offering the streaming video platform. Netflix made Blockbuster dance to its tunes. Netflix, currently valued at $150 billion, changed its business model twice by cannibalizing its core services, shifting from mail-in- DVD service to subscription service to streaming video subscription service. This strategic renewal is one of the critical reasons for Netflix to become a valuable company and one of the pioneers

input: What is YARN?
output:
YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator) is a resource management framework for distributed computing frameworks. YARN is an acronym for "Yet Another Resource Negotiator".

In the Hadoop framework, MapReduce is a programming model for processing large data sets using a network of commodity computers. The MapReduce API runs on top of HDFS, and interprets and breaks up the input data into small pieces called "mappers" and runs them in parallel across the cluster, then gathers the results of all the mappers together and writes them to HDFS, and then repeats.

YARN is a framework that lets other applications and frameworks call MapReduce programs.
label: YARN (“Yet Another Resource Negotiator“) is the Hadoop operating system that enables to manage resources and schedule jobs in Hadoop.

The German region (Deutschschweiz) is roughly in the east, north, and centre; the French part (la Romandie) in the west; and the Italian area (Svizzera italiana) in the south. The treaty was negotiated between the Allied and Associated Powers and the German Empire at Compiègne, and was formally ratified on 18 July 1919. In contrast, continuous variables include infinitely uncountable values, for example, a variable over a non-empty range of real numbers. 

According to the number of objective functions, an optimisation problem is classified as single or multi-objective. On the other hand, a multi-objective one considers two or more objectives simultaneously, which means the interaction between objectives has to be considered.

input: Can you write a brief summary for the book "Braving the Wilderness" by Brene Brown?
output: Brene Brown is a researcher and consultant who studies "The Power of vulnerability". She identifies courage, authenticity, belonging, and risk-taking as the foundational qualities necessary for success. Brown emphasizes the need to be kind to ourselves in order to be kind to others. She states that vulnerability is not weakness, but rather it is a courageous act that allows the human spirit to soar. Brown believes that authenticity is the key to unlocking our hidden strengths and that belonging is essential to our well-being. She stresses the importance of being honest with others and ourselves about who we are, what we like, and what we want and shares numerous examples of how others have transformed through vulnerability. Finally, Brown identifies risk-taking as a courageous act that is necessary to our growth and reminds us that mistakes are part of the process of learning.
label: Braving the Wilderness is a book about belonging, identity, and leadership. A core idea is that if you are courageous enough to stand alone in the name of the virtues and values you believe in, you can actually create more belonging for others. To brave the wilderness is not to go into the woods armored and ready to fight, but with an open heart and conviction steadying your spine.

input: Is it acceptable to sign a cappella (without musical accompaniment) at a community musical theater audition?
output: While it is not common, it is not unheard of to sign a cappella. If you are a trained singer, and there is a part for you, it is recommended that you sing a cappella (without musical accompaniment) to ensure that you stick to the key and range of the song. The audience will often judge the singer's range by how well they can sing without music. A cappella singing is not uncommon in the Broadway musical scene, and in community musical theater auditions, as a singer's range is often defined early on in the audition. However, if you are singing a jazz or swing song, it is recommended that you sing with music.
label: No, this is usually not considered acceptable. Auditioners for local, community musical theater are usually expected to provide sheet music -- clearly marked with their specific cut of the material -- for the audition accompanist. This may be a physical, printed copy of the music, or an electronic version provided on a tablet computer such as an iPad. In some cases, the company holding the auditions may also allow you to play recorded accompaniment at the audition. However, this should also be avoided unless the audition instructions specifically state that this is acceptable.

input: What kind of socks do grizzlies wear?
output: Grizzly bears have thick fur that protects their toes and allows them to walk on snow. They also have little paws called "claws" on their toes to help them grip tree branches. This allows them to walk on the roots of trees to find food. Grizzly bears also live in the mountains and near the coast. They don't need to go to the beach to enjoy the sun. They find shade underneath large trees. They like to sleep during the day and are active at night. They like to make their own den which is usually in a tree. They will often dig under a tree first to see if it is hollow. If it is hollow, they will make a den inside. If it is not hollow, they will try to build one. If they find a good shelter, they will take a nap inside. They will wake up in the morning to eat. They will eat anything they can find, like roots, bugs, berries, salmon, and fish! They are very good at hunting.
label: None, they have bear feet!

input: Is the recording of a person's last words reliable?
output: In general, recording of a person's last words is a reliable way to capture their last wishes.  However, in some instances there may be some ambiguity as to what the last words actually are.  In these instances, a living will may be used as an alternative to recording one's last words.  A living will is a legal document that allows the individual to express their wishes as to whether they would like their life to be intentionally ended, or to be prolonged, in the event that they are diagnosed with a terminal illness.  Ultimately, the decision should be left up to the individual, and not the scope of these guidelines.
label: Sometimes it is, while other times it may contain errors or deliberately misquoted.
